-- Node: bt-taco-trali (2 field(s) changed)
UPDATE decision_nodes SET data = '{"type":"info","module":5,"title":"TACO vs TRALI","body":"**Both Present Similarly:** Dyspnea, hypoxia, bilateral infiltrates during or shortly after transfusion. The critical difference is the underlying mechanism.\n\n---\n\n**TACO (Transfusion-Associated Circulatory Overload)**\n*Volume overload → heart can''t handle the extra fluid*\n\n- **Mechanism:** Too much volume for the heart/kidneys to handle\n- **Think:** Flash pulmonary edema from CHF exacerbation\n- **Timing:** During transfusion or within 12 hours\n- **Key findings:** JVD present, hypertensive, elevated BNP\n- **Treatment:** Diuretics WORK (Lasix 20-40 mg IV)\n\n---\n\n**TRALI (Transfusion-Related Acute Lung Injury)**\n*Immune reaction → lung capillaries leak*\n\n- **Mechanism:** Donor antibodies activate recipient neutrophils → lung injury\n- **Think:** ARDS-like picture, non-cardiogenic edema\n- **Timing:** During transfusion or within 6 hours\n- **Key findings:** NO JVD, often hypotensive, normal BNP\n- **Treatment:** Supportive only. Diuretics DO NOT help.\n\n---\n\n**The Key Differentiator: BNP (B-type Natriuretic Peptide)**\n- BNP elevated → TACO (heart is stretched)\n- BNP normal/low → TRALI (heart is fine, lungs are injured)\n- BNP ratio post/pre transfusion >1.5 strongly suggests TACO","citation":[6,7],"options":[{"label":"TACO Details","next":"bt-taco"},{"label":"TRALI Details","next":"bt-trali"},{"label":"Back to Complications","next":"bt-complications-overview"}],"summary":"TACO = volume overload (BNP high, diuretics work); TRALI = lung injury (BNP normal, supportive care only)"}'::jsonb
WHERE id = 'bt-taco-trali' AND tree_id = 'blood-transfusions';

-- Node: bt-taco (2 field(s) changed)
UPDATE decision_nodes SET data = '{"type":"info","module":5,"title":"TACO (Circulatory Overload)","body":"**TACO = Transfusion-Associated Circulatory Overload**\n\n**What is it?**\nVolume overload causing cardiogenic pulmonary edema. Think of it like giving too much IV fluid to a CHF patient.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- Patient has underlying cardiac or renal dysfunction\n- Transfusion adds volume the heart can''t handle\n- Result: Elevated hydrostatic pressure → fluid leaks into lungs\n\n**Diagnosis (3+ within 12h of transfusion):**\n- Dyspnea, orthopnea, cough\n- Hypoxemia (O2 sat <90% on room air)\n- Hypertension, tachycardia, peripheral edema\n- **Elevated BNP** (B-type natriuretic peptide) or NT-proBNP\n- Abnormal echo (low EF, dilated ventricles)\n\n**Treatment:**\n1. **STOP transfusion** immediately\n2. Sit patient upright\n3. Supplemental O2 or ventilation\n4. **Furosemide 20-40 mg IV** for diuresis\n5. Monitor urine output\n6. Vasodilator (nitroglycerin) if hypertensive\n\n**Prevention:**\n- Slow transfusion rate (<1 mL/kg/hour in high-risk)\n- Consider concurrent diuretic if heart failure/renal disease\n- Single-unit transfusion strategy in elderly","citation":[6,7],"options":[{"label":"Back to TACO vs TRALI","next":"bt-taco-trali"}],"summary":"TACO: volume overload → cardiogenic edema; BNP elevated; treat with diuretics, O2, upright positioning"}'::jsonb
WHERE id = 'bt-taco' AND tree_id = 'blood-transfusions';

-- Node: bt-trali (2 field(s) changed)
UPDATE decision_nodes SET data = '{"type":"info","module":5,"title":"TRALI (Acute Lung Injury)","body":"**TRALI = Transfusion-Related Acute Lung Injury**\n\n**What is it?**\nAn immune reaction that damages the lung capillaries, causing non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema. The heart is fine, but the lungs are leaking.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- **Immune (80-85%):** Donor plasma contains antibodies (anti-HLA or anti-HNA) that activate the recipient''s neutrophils\n- Activated neutrophils sequester in pulmonary capillaries → release toxic mediators → capillary leak\n- Result: Protein-rich fluid floods alveoli (like ARDS)\n\n**Diagnosis:**\n- **Timing:** During or within 6 hours of transfusion\n- Sudden dyspnea, severe hypoxemia\n- Fever, hypotension (not hypertension like TACO), tachycardia\n- Bilateral infiltrates on CXR\n- **NO JVD** (heart is not overloaded)\n- **Normal BNP** (heart is fine)\n- Normal LV function on echo\n\n**Treatment:**\n1. **STOP transfusion**\n2. Supportive care only\n3. O2, mechanical ventilation if needed\n4. **DO NOT give diuretics** (won''t help, may cause harm)\n5. Usually resolves 48-96 hours\n\n**Mortality:** 6-12%\n\n**Prevention:**\n- Male-only plasma programs (females with prior pregnancies have more HLA antibodies)\n- Leukoreduction of products","citation":[6,7],"options":[{"label":"Back to TACO vs TRALI","next":"bt-taco-trali"}],"summary":"TRALI: immune lung injury → non-cardiogenic edema; BNP normal, no JVD; supportive care only; resolves 48-96h"}'::jsonb
WHERE id = 'bt-trali' AND tree_id = 'blood-transfusions';

-- Node: bt-ahtr (2 field(s) changed)
UPDATE decision_nodes SET data = '{"type":"info","module":4,"title":"Acute Hemolytic Reaction","body":"**ACUTE HEMOLYTIC TRANSFUSION REACTION**\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- ABO incompatibility (most common cause)\n- Host antibodies bind donor RBCs → intravascular hemolysis\n- Can occur with just a few milliliters of blood\n\n**Classic Triad (rarely all present):**\n- Fever\n- Flank/back pain\n- Dark red/brown urine (hemoglobinuria)\n\n**Other Signs:**\n- Anxiety, chest pain, dyspnea\n- Hypotension (under anesthesia may be only sign)\n- Uncontrolled bleeding (DIC = disseminated intravascular coagulation)\n- Pain at infusion site\n\n**Labs:**\n- **DAT (Direct Antiglobulin Test, also called Direct Coombs) = POSITIVE**\n  - This test detects antibodies attached to red blood cells\n- Free hemoglobin in plasma/urine\n- Low haptoglobin\n- Elevated LDH, indirect bilirubin\n\n**EMERGENCY TREATMENT:**\n1. **STOP TRANSFUSION IMMEDIATELY**\n2. Maintain IV access (new line)\n3. Verify patient ID vs blood product\n4. **Aggressive crystalloid** (maintain urine output >200 mL/hr)\n5. **Sodium bicarbonate** 250-500 mg IV (alkalinize urine, protect kidneys)\n6. Furosemide or mannitol for diuresis\n7. Treat DIC: FFP, cryo, platelets\n8. Notify blood bank, repeat type & screen\n\n**Prognosis:** Survivable with aggressive support; depends on degree of kidney injury","citation":[8],"options":[{"label":"Back to Complications","next":"bt-complications-overview"}],"summary":"Acute hemolytic: STOP transfusion, verify ID, aggressive fluids + bicarb for renal protection; Direct Coombs positive"}'::jsonb
WHERE id = 'bt-ahtr' AND tree_id = 'blood-transfusions';

-- Node: bt-fnhtr (2 field(s) changed)
UPDATE decision_nodes SET data = '{"type":"info","module":4,"title":"Febrile Non-Hemolytic Reaction","body":"**FEBRILE NON-HEMOLYTIC TRANSFUSION REACTION (FNHTR)**\n\n**Most common transfusion reaction**\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- Cytokine accumulation during storage (especially platelets)\n- OR recipient HLA alloantibodies reacting against donor white blood cells\n\n**Diagnosis (this is a diagnosis of exclusion):**\n- **Fever:** ≥38°C OR rise ≥1°C from baseline within 4h\n- Moderate/severe: ≥39°C OR rise ≥1.5°C, chills/rigors\n- **DAT (Direct Antiglobulin Test/Direct Coombs) = NEGATIVE**\n  - This rules out hemolytic reaction\n- Hemolysis labs normal (LDH, bilirubin, haptoglobin)\n- Must rule out: Hemolytic reaction, TRALI, sepsis\n\n**Treatment:**\n1. Pause transfusion, assess patient\n2. Antipyretic (acetaminophen)\n3. If no other serious reaction → can resume transfusion\n4. Only ~10% have recurrent episodes\n\n**Prevention:**\n- Prestorage leukoreduction (removes white blood cells, reduces cytokines)\n- Use fresher blood when possible\n- Premedicate with antipyretic in high-risk patients\n\n**Key Point:** Must rule out hemolytic reaction (check DAT) and TRALI before diagnosing FNHTR","citation":[6],"options":[{"label":"Back to Complications","next":"bt-complications-overview"}],"summary":"FNHTR: most common reaction; fever + Direct Coombs negative; treat with antipyretic; can resume if no other reaction"}'::jsonb
WHERE id = 'bt-fnhtr' AND tree_id = 'blood-transfusions';

